<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a .gitignore file?", answer: "A .gitignore file tells Git which files and directories to exclude from version control. It uses glob patterns to match file paths. When a file matches a pattern in .gitignore, Git will not track it, show it in git status, or include it in commits. This prevents build artifacts, dependency directories, environment files, IDE settings, and OS-generated files from cluttering your repository." },
  { question: "Can I combine multiple .gitignore templates?", answer: "Yes. This generator lets you select multiple templates and combines them into a single .gitignore file. A typical full-stack project might combine Ruby, Node.js, macOS, and VS Code templates. Each template section is clearly labeled with a comment so you can identify which rules came from which template." },
  { question: "Where should I place the .gitignore file?", answer: "Place .gitignore in the root directory of your Git repository. Git applies the rules recursively to all subdirectories unless a pattern starts with a slash, which anchors it to the directory containing the .gitignore file. You can also create .gitignore files in subdirectories for rules specific to that part of the project." },
  { question: "Why is my .env file in the .gitignore?", answer: "The .env file typically contains environment-specific configuration including database URLs, API keys, and other secrets. Committing .env to version control exposes these secrets to anyone with repository access. Every language template in this generator includes .env in the ignore list. Instead, provide a .env.example file with placeholder values that developers can copy and fill in locally." },
  { question: "What happens if I add a .gitignore rule for a file already tracked by Git?", answer: "Adding a pattern to .gitignore does not remove already-tracked files from the repository. You must explicitly untrack them with 'git rm --cached filename' to remove the file from Git's index while keeping it on disk. After that, the .gitignore rule will prevent Git from tracking it in future commits." }
]) %>

